PREAMBLE
========

The LaTeX Project Public License (LPPL) is the primary license under which the
LaTeX kernel and the base LaTeX packages are distributed.

You may use this license for any work of which you hold the copyright and which
you wish to distribute.  This license may be particularly suitable if your work
is TeX-related (such as a LaTeX package), but it is written in such a way that
you can use it even if your work is unrelated to TeX.

The section `WHETHER AND HOW TO DISTRIBUTE WORKS UNDER THIS LICENSE', below,
gives instructions, examples, and recommendations for authors who are
considering distributing their works under this license.

This license gives conditions under which a work may be distributed and
modifies the normal process of modifying a work.  Instead of directly changing
a work that you have received, you are encouraged to copy the work and make any
changes to your copy.  You may then distribute the modified copy under the same
license, either changing its name or maintaining the same name as the original
work.

This license also provides for what we call the \emph{maintenance} of a work,
which is the ability for other people to take over the responsibility of
developing the work when the original author is no longer able or willing to do
so.  Maintenance under this license is quite different from traditional
software maintenance, so please read the `MAINTENANCE' section carefully.

The LaTeX Project Public License is copyright (C) 1999 2002-2008
The LaTeX3 Project.  All rights reserved.


DEFINITIONS
===========

In this license document the following terms are used:

  `Work'
    Any work being distributed under this License.  (This document is an
    example of a Work.)

  `Derived Work'
    Any work that under any applicable law is derived from the Work.

  `Modification'
    Any procedure that produces a Derived Work under any applicable law -- for
    example, the production of a file containing an identical copy of part of
    the Work, or the production of a file containing a translated version of
    part of the Work.

  `Modify'
    To apply any procedure that produces a Derived Work under any applicable
    law.

  `Distribution'
    Making copies of the Work available from one person to another, in whole or
    in part.  Distribution includes (but is not limited to) making any electronic
    components of the Work accessible by file transfer protocols such as FTP or
    HTTP or by shared file systems such as Sun's Network File System (NFS).

  `Compiled Work'
    A version of the Work that has been processed into a form where it is
    directly usable on a computer system.  This processing may include using
    installation facilities provided by the Work, transformations of the Work,
    copying of components of the Work, or other activities.  Note that this
    license places no restrictions on the format of a Compiled Work.

  `Current Maintainer'
    A person who is named as such in the Work.  If there is no Current
    Maintainer then the Work is `unmaintained'.

  `Base Interpreter'
    A program or process that is normally needed for running or interpreting a
    part or the whole of the Work.

    A Base Interpreter may depend on external components but these do not form
    part of the Base Interpreter as long as they are not packaged with it as a
    single unit.

    A Base Interpreter may be (but is not limited to) a `TeX engine' (such as
    TeX itself, pdfTeX, XeTeX, LuaTeX, etc.), or a format (such as Plain TeX,
    LaTeX, AMS-TeX, ConTeXt, etc.), or a `shell' (such as a Unix shell, a DOS
    shell, an MSWindows shell, etc.), or a graphics interpreter (such as
    MetaPost, MetaFont, GhostScript, etc.).


CONDITIONS ON DISTRIBUTION AND MODIFICATION
===========================================

    1.  Activities other than distribution and/or modification of the Work are
        not covered by this license; they are outside its scope.  In particular,
        the act of running the Work is not restricted and no requirements are
        made concerning any offers of support for the Work.

    2.  You may distribute a complete, unmodified copy of the Work as you
        received it.  Distribution of only part of the Work is considered
        modification of the Work, and no right to distribute such a Derived Work
        may be assumed under the terms of this license.

    3.  You may distribute a Compiled Work that has been generated from a
        complete, unmodified copy of the Work as distributed under Clause 2
        above, as long as that Compiled Work is distributed in such a way that
        the recipients may install the Compiled Work on their system exactly as
        it would have been installed if they generated a Compiled Work directly
        from the Work.

    4.  If you are the Current Maintainer of the Work, you may, without
        restriction, modify the Work, thus creating a Derived Work.  You may, in
        addition, without restriction, distribute the Derived Work under the
        terms of Clause 2 above.  Distribution of only part of the Work under
        Clause 3 does not count as a modification and does not require this
        clause.

    5.  If you are not the Current Maintainer of the Work, you may distribute a
        Derived Work provided the conditions in Clause 6, below, are met.

    6.  You may distribute a Derived Work under the same conditions as in
        Clause 2 above provided that

        a.  Your Derived Work is distributed as a whole, meaning that all files
            that it contains must be distributed under this license.  If you
            want to distribute parts of your Derived Work under another license,
            then you must ensure that your Derived Work is clearly distinguishable
            from the Work, and that those parts of your Derived Work that you want
            to distribute under another license do not contain any substantial
            part of the Work.

        b.  You ensure that every copy of the Derived Work you distribute
            contains a prominent notice that the Derived Work differs from the
            Work.  Such notices must appear in each file of the Derived Work that
            differs from the Work.

        c.  You ensure that the Derived Work is not represented as being the
            original Work, either by explicit statement or implication.  The
            Derived Work must be given a different name from the Work.

        d.  You ensure that the Derived Work contains the location of the
            original Work (as it was distributed by the Current Maintainer) in the
            distribution information of the Derived Work.

    7.  If the Work is unmaintained, you may become the Current Maintainer by
        adding yourself to the list of Current Maintainers of the Work in the
        Derived Work in accordance with Clause 6 above.

        a.  If the Work is maintained, you can only become the Current
            Maintainer if the former Current Maintainer agrees to pass
            maintenance of the Work to you.

    8.  You may distribute a Derived Work that has been otherwise modified,
        even without respecting Clause 6 above, provided that you distribute the
        Derived Work with a request for permission from the Current Maintainer to
        distribute the Derived Work as part of the Work.

    9.  If you become the Current Maintainer of the Work, you should change the
        `Maintained by' field in the Work to your own name.  You should also
        ensure that the previous Maintainer is acknowledged.

    10. Whenever this license requires that a Derived Work be distributed under
        the terms of this license, the Derived Work may include files
        redistributable under different terms, provided that the new terms
        acknowledge the status of the Derived Work as a Derived Work of the
        Work.  That is, the new terms must acknowledge the source and must allow
        modification and redistribution of the Derived Work under the same terms
        as this license.


MAINTENANCE
===========

The Work has the status `maintained' if the Work is being maintained by at
least one Current Maintainer, or if the Work contains a statement that the Work
is maintained.  If the Work has the status `maintained' then the Current
Maintainer may make any changes to the Work, and these changes are considered
part of the Work.

The Work has the status `unmaintained' if it contains a statement that it is no
longer maintained.  If the Work has the status `unmaintained' then correctable
bugs may be fixed by anyone.  A `bug' is any malfunction (or potential
malfunction) of the Work that interferes with its ability to perform its
documented tasks.

If the Work is unmaintained and the copyright holder(s) agree, a person who has
corrected bugs may be named the Current Maintainer of the repaired Work.


