TO THE EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, THE WORK IS PROVIDED `AS IS',
WITHOUT WARRANTY OF ANY KIND, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING, WITHOUT
LIMITATION, ANY WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR
PURPOSE, OR NON-INFRINGEMENT.

IN NO EVENT WILL THE COPYRIGHT HOLDER, THE AUTHORS, OR ANY OTHER PARTY WHO MAY
COPY AND/OR (RE)DISTRIBUTE THE WORK AS PERMITTED IN SECTION 6 ABOVE, BE LIABLE
TO YOU FOR ANY DAMAGES ARISING OUT OF THE USE OF THE WORK, WHETHER ARISING FROM
TORT (INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE), CONTRACT, OR ANY OTHER THEORY OF LIABILITY, EVEN
IF SUCH PARTIES HAVE BEEN ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGE.


WHETHER AND HOW TO DISTRIBUTE WORKS UNDER THIS LICENSE
======================================================

The following applies to any work that contains the notice

    This work may be distributed and/or modified under the conditions
    of the LaTeX Project Public License,
    either version 1.3c of this license or (at your option) any later
    version.  The latest version of this license is in
      http://www.latex-project.org/lppl.txt
    and version 1.3c or later is part of all distributions of LaTeX
    version 2008-05-04 or later.

and that is not part of the Work.  If your work is unrelated to TeX, and it does
not contain a notice as above, then you may omit the remainder of this section.

    1.  If you are the Current Maintainer of the work, you should include a
        statement on how people can contact you in case they have questions or
        need support.  If you are not the Current Maintainer of the Work, you
        should obtain permission from the Current Maintainer before distributing
        your modification.

    2.  Your distribution should contain a copy of this license and a statement
        of the status of the Work (maintained or unmaintained).

    3.  If you are not the Current Maintainer, you need to make sure you do not
        transfer the right of maintenance to another person.  This means that, if
        you plan to distribute a modification, then your modified work should
        include the name of the Current Maintainer in the `Maintained by...' field.

    4.  If your work is intended for use with TeX or related programs, we
        recommend that you include a `\ProvidesPackage' or `\ProvidesClass' (or
        similar) macro stating the name, version, and date of the Work.

    5.  If the Work is intended to be used with a format (such as LaTeX or a
        similar system), we recommend that you include a `\ProvidesPackage' or
        `\ProvidesClass' (or similar) macro in your file so that the version of
        the Work can be easily determined.  This will help users see whether they
        are using the latest version of the Work.

    6.  If you maintain a program that requires other programs to run, you
        should specify in your documentation which programs are required.

    7.  If you are not the Current Maintainer but would like to become one,
        you can ask the Current Maintainer to relinquish maintenance to you.
        If the Work is unmaintained, and you would like to take over maintenance,
        you can change the `Maintained by' field to your name.  In doing so you
        should include a statement explaining how people can contact you.

    8.  If you are not the Current Maintainer and you want to make a
        modification that does not create a Derived Work, you should contact the
        Current Maintainer and offer to collaborate with him or her.  Please do
        not distribute your modification separately, as that will confuse users.

    9.  The Work has status `maintained' if the Current Maintainer is willing to
        accept bug reports and fix bugs.  If the Work is unmaintained, please
        attempt to coordinate with other users to find a new maintainer before
        you take over maintenance.  This will help to ensure that the Work remains
        useful to users even after the original maintainer is no longer able to
        maintain it.

The LaTeX Project Public License, LPPL, was designed to address the special
considerations associated with writing and distributing programs for TeX,
including macro packages, fonts, and documentation, and the files generated by
these programs.  In addition to the general types of modifications of Programs
and Documentations that are usually permitted under free software licenses, this
license specifically allows for configuration changes that enable the Work to
work with other programs, configuration files, and build scripts.
